gro: The Scholar, The Gypsy, The Priest (1851) brings a renewed focus on a formally inventive and original text for scholars of the nineteenth-century autobiographical novel and travelogue. This edition reflects and develops research that anchors Borrow’s energetically eccentric vision in a range of notable contexts. The scholarly introduction gives readers unfamiliar with the formidably prolific Borrow an opportunity to discover more about this author’s career at home and abroad (as a translator for the British and Foreign Bible Society), his stylistic innovations, and how Lavengro evokes a ‘wild England’ that became crucial for admirers in the next century such as D.H. Lawrence, Ford Madox Ford, and Virginia Woolf.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh1 aRadford, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079764040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978139951688440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781399516884423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781399516884/original  a978-3-11-079764-0  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles